Since you need **three** themes, `AppThemeBinding` won't work (it only supports light/dark). Use the **ResourceDictionary swap** approach instead.

## 1. Define three theme dictionaries with matching keys

Create a `Themes/` folder. Each dictionary uses the same `x:Key` values:

**LightTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">White</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">#333333</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#2196F3</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```
```csharp
namespace MyApp.Themes;
public partial class LightTheme : ResourceDictionary
{
    public LightTheme() => InitializeComponent();
}
```

**DarkTheme.xaml** — same keys, dark values:
```xml
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">#121212</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">#EEEEEE</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#BB86FC</Color>
```

**HighContrastTheme.xaml** — same keys, high-contrast values:
```xml
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">Black</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">White</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">Yellow</Color>
```

Each needs a matching `.xaml.cs` code-behind calling `InitializeComponent()`.

## 2. Use `DynamicResource` everywhere (not `StaticResource`)

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackgroundColor}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryTextColor}" />
    <Button Text="Go"   BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" />
</ContentPage>
```

## 3. Create a theme-switching helper

```csharp
public static class ThemeManager
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        ResourceDictionary theme = themeName switch
        {
            "Dark"         => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast"  => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _              => new LightTheme()
        };

        var merged = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
        merged.Clear();
        merged.Add(theme);

        // Persist the user's choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themeName);
    }
}
```

## 4. Restore on startup (in `App` constructor)

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeManager.ApplyTheme(Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light"));
}
```

## 5. Settings page picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        ItemsSource="{Binding ThemeOptions}"
        SelectedItem="{Binding SelectedTheme}" />
```
```csharp
ThemePicker.SelectedIndexChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedItem is string theme)
        ThemeManager.ApplyTheme(theme);
};
```

## Key gotchas

- **Every `x:Key` must exist in all three dictionaries** — a missing key silently falls back to defaults.
- **Android:** ensure `MainActivity` includes `ConfigChanges.UiMode` or theme events won't fire and the activity restarts.
- **Never use `StaticResource`** for themed values — it freezes at first load and won't update on swap.
